  "prompt": "What universities does W&T offshore recruit new grads from? What majors are they looking for?",
  "response": "W&T Offshore, an independent oil and natural gas acquisition, exploration, and development company, typically recruits new graduates with relevant educational backgrounds to support their operations. While specific recruitment details may vary by year, they generally seek candidates from universities with strong engineering, geosciences, and business programs. Commonly targeted universities and majors include:\n\n1. **Universities**:\n   - **University of Texas at Austin**: Known for its petroleum engineering and geosciences programs.\n   - **Texas A&M University**: Offers strong petroleum engineering, geology, and business programs.\n   - **Louisiana State University (LSU)**: Renowned for petroleum engineering and geosciences.\n   - **University of Oklahoma**: Offers top-tier petroleum engineering and geology programs.\n   - **Colorado School of Mines**: Specializes in engineering and applied sciences, particularly in energy and natural resources.\n   - **University of Houston**: Known for engineering and geosciences programs relevant to the energy sector.\n   - **Texas Tech University**: Offers strong engineering and geosciences degrees.\n   - **University of Louisiana at Lafayette**: Known for petroleum engineering and related fields.\n\n2. **Majors**:\n   - **Petroleum Engineering**\n   - **Geology/Geosciences**\n   - **Chemical Engineering**\n   - **Mechanical Engineering**\n   - **Civil Engineering**\n   - **Environmental Science/Engineering**\n   - **Business Administration (with a focus on energy or finance)**\n   - **Data Science/Analytics** (increasingly important for the energy sector)\n\nW&T Offshore often collaborates with university career centers, attends career fairs, and engages with student organizations to recruit talent. Candidates with internships or relevant project experience in the energy sector are typically preferred. For the most accurate and up-to-date information, it\u2019s best to check their official career page or contact their recruiting team directly.",
